column1: Who will win the election for Georgia's 7th Congressional District in 2020?
column5: ['The Democratic Party candidate', 'The Republican Party candidate', 'Someone else']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
Strong Republican seat.
Based on recent polling
The huge surge in voting suggest dems get this seat
Democrats had a solid chance at this seat as they barely lost in 2018.

Average of: https://forecast.decisiondeskhq.com/house/H2020GA07 -- 57.2% https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-election-forecast/house/georgia/7/ -- 46% https://projects.economist.com/us-2020-forecast/house/georgia-7 -- 62%

Cook Political rates this lean Democrat though it a traditionally Republican area. The Republican won in 2018 by only 450 votes. Should be close. https://www.11alive.com/article/news/politics/elections/georgia-house-of-represenatives-races-in-2020/85-0dc37013-46a8-4086-a608-ff162cf63664
Dems win here big.

Crowd forecast underestimates Democratic chances here, because: 1) Suburban district trending blue, In 2018 race, GOP incumbent won by skin of his teeth 2) Demographic changes. District is now less than 50% White. 3) Solid Democratic candidate who's considered a moderate, so is an idealogical fit for her district. 4) GOP candidate does not have a political resume nor much name recognition 5) Dem has big lead in fundraising
The Dem is running again for an open seat, after losing a close race. Well funded and organized. I am in Atlanta, near her district.
Polls are old, national scene favors Democrats, and decision desk and the one old poll both lean Democrat so I'm giving Dem the slight edge for now until we get better polling.
Lack of recent polling and no clear margin opened in past polls -> updating closer to 50/50
Cook Political Report ratings change from Toss Up to Lean D
Bordeaux only lost by 433 votes last time. https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2020/07/23/georgia-7th-district-congress
Slightly Republican ; but still toss up.. Let's see
Race between Bourdeaux and Woodall was incredibly close in 2018, 140,010 vs 140,443, respectively despite Bourdeaux being down in the polls by 6 points. She is now +3.
Higher-income could mean that they have had retirees, or people escaping the bigger cities to settle there recently.

I think the challenger has a great chance this time, she came really really close against the current incumbent last time out!
Slightly Republican ; but still toss up.. Let's see

This is Bourdeaux's second bite at the apple. Two years ago she barely lost to Woodall, who won with 50.1%. Woodall had larger margins of victory in previous elections. So a strong Dem turnout will carry her over the top.
Georgia will decide to make America great again, and to keep it great. Thank you Georgia!
Just an old sweet song Keeps Georgia on my mind

The last race was decided by .02 percent after winning by twenty points two years earlier. This district is prime suburbia, a place where Trump is toxic right now with a growing non-white population. No way this race doesn't go blue.
Looked at unemployment rate, 11% and composition of population. The Dem has a good chance.
Updating.

This seat went Republican by 433 votes last election cycle, which was a Bordeaux vs. Woodall. With Woodall retiring, name recognition swings in favor of his last opponent (who lost on the narrowest of margins). With the current political climate, a Dem lead is unlikely to shrink in the coming months.

D leading narrowly in the polls (https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/house/georgia/7/) and not so narrowly in fundraising (https://www.opensecrets.org/races/candidates?cycle=2020&id=GA07&spec=N)
Slight edge to the Democrat. This will be her second general election, having lost by only 433 votes in 2018 to a republican incumbent. I believe she flips the district from red to blue.
The Dem barely lost last election, a few hundred votes. She is building on that campaign. It will be close, but Bourdeoux is strong. I live in GA.
